3/1/00
  The new dpi code after ver 166 continue to have bad PidBuf problem.
  Reverted to ver 166 (from top of tree).

  Turned statmux to account for long delay.
  Buffer problem still occurs during the switch.  This is because the next AD's
  has not been received before we reach EOS of the previous AD due to the gap.
  As a result, tsDelay will be assumed to be zero in this case, with position
  deadTime.  This is definitely WRONG!

  Solution: we need to add data field in ChanInfo to indicate expected channel
  start up time.  TsDelay will be initialized using this field, if present.
  Also need to initial startingFlag appropriately based on closedGopFlag.

  A more difficult problem is the leading B pictures in closed GOP case.
  We need to wait for one more picture, after the I, to find the starting PTS,
  and hence tsDelay.  Unfortunately we only process one picture (first one)
  in CHAN_ON mode.  If we delay the decision for the first I, then we will
  always have one more picture wait on the queue, until the next switch.
  Currently we just let it be this way to minimize code change.

  The above method doesn't quite work!

  Use a tsDelayCnt instead:
  - For free start channel, set it to 0.
  - For non-free start channel, init it to 1.
  - For the first I picture with tr==0, compute tsDelay and set tsDelayCnt to 0.
    Adjust PTS/DTS of current picture.
  - For the first I picture with tr>0, postpone processing of this picture,
    and set tsDelayCnt to 2.  When the next picture (tr should be 0) arrives,
    compute tsDelay, and go back to adjust PTS/DTS of previous and current
    pictures.  Set tsDelayCnt to 0.

  On second thought, the current EOS splice implementation has several
  disadvantages:
    - Doesn't quite follow what the other modes do => more changes
      (Actually a differnt channel start up method is required.)
    - Cannot fix field parity conflict at splice point in some cases.
    - Cannot actually calculate dead time
    - Cannot correctly give forced switch signal

  A differernt implementation is therefore considered:
    FG processing:
      When a picture with EOS is found, set spliceReady flag.
      When an anchor picture is received, send all previous pictures
        (until not possible).
        - Actually you will always be able to send all but the last anchor
          picture because any pending PTS would have been resolved by the
          next reference frame.
      Simply wait on receiving B picture.

    BG processing:
      Simple hold as many pictures as possible in buffer (until cleared by
      buffer overflow).
      Also update spliceReady flag as normal.
      If FG becomes ready, get the first entry candidate found.  Compute either
      tsDelay or deadTime.  Do splice.

   Bug found in procBgSpliceChan(): when bndryPicFnd is set, arrival of
   next picture will make BG to be spliceReady.  We also adjust spliceTime
   if there is a leading B picture.  We should have only adjust if leading B
   exists and this is a closed GOP!


